\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa240\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx720\hyphpar0\faauto\ls19\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {Eric Howker appeals from the decision given on 4 May 2001 by a Social Security Commissioner, Mr Patrick Howell QC. Thereby the Commissioner dismissed Mr Howker\rquote s appeal fr
om the decision on 6 June 1997 of a social security appeal tribunal sitting in Sutton, confirming that Mr Howker\rquote 
s previous entitlement to incapacity benefit had been correctly reviewed and terminated from 5 February 1997. The tribunal rejected Mr Howker\rquote s
 argument that he should continue to be entitled to benefit by reason of a provision in regulation 27(b) of the Social Security (Incapacity for Work) (General) Regulations 1995 (\'93the 1995 Regulations\'94
). That provision was repealed and not re-enacted by the Social Security (Incapacity for Work and Miscellaneous Amendments) Regulations 1996 (\'93the 1996 Regulations\'94
), but Mr Howker challenged the validity of the new regulation 27. This appeal is brought with the permission of the Commissioner, who made trenchant criticisms of the conduct of officials in the Department of Social Security (\'93the Department\'94
) in the course of the making of the 1996 Regulations. The issue raised on this appeal is whether by reason of that conduct the new regulation 27 was not validly
 made by the Secretary of State with the result that the exemption in regulation 27(b) of the 1995 Regulations continues in force.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}I must now set out the background facts which I take largely from the unchallenged findings made by the Commissioner in his full and lucid decision.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab}}\pard \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx720\hyphpar0\faauto\ls19\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
Mr Howker, who is in his late 50s, has for some years been suffering from heart trouble and other health problems. He received invalidity benefit from 1994. That benefit was replaced by incapacity benefit on 13 April 1995. The princ
ipal test for that benefit is what is known as the \'93all work test\'94
, a points-based test designed to determine whether someone is incapable of taking paid employment of some kind. Mr Howker was found not to satisfy that test. However, the 1995 Regulations c
ontained in regulation 27 a provision for entitlement to benefit in certain exceptional cases where the all work test was not satisfied. By regulation 27:
\par }\pard\plain \s24\qj \li720\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\'93A person who does not satisfy the all work test shall be treated as incapable of work if in the opin
ion of a doctor approved by the Secretary of State \endash 
\par  ... 
\par (b) he suffers from some specific disease or bodily or mental disablement and, by reasons [sic] of such disease or disablement, there would be a substantial risk to the mental or physical health of any person if he was found capable of work ... \'94

\par }\pard\plain \s25\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa240\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {
Paragraph (b) applied to Mr Howker, as was accepted by the Department. However, in an unreported judgment of Collins J. on 12 September 1996 in }{\i R v. Secretary of State for Social Security ex parte Moule}{ reg
ulation 27 was held to be invalid as outside the enabling legislation, in that it provided for the question of deemed incapacity to be determined by a doctor approved by the Secretary of State rather than by an adjudication officer as required by the legi
slation.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa240\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx0\hyphpar0\faauto\ls19\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {
Consequent on that decision the Department proposed alterations to regulation 27. The proposals were to make the question whether the conditions for exemption were satisfied one for the determination of the adjudication officer and to recast those 
conditions by, amongst other things, deleting paragraph (b) without replacement. None of the remaining exempting conditions applies to Mr Howker, as he accepts.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 5.\tab}The power to make regulations in this field is vested in the Secretary of State. By section 171D Social Security Contributions and Benefits Act 1992 as amended:

\par }\pard\plain \s24\qj \li720\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\'93
 ... Regulations may provide that a person shall be treated as capable of work, or as incapable of work, in such cases or circumstances as may be prescribed.\'94
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 6.\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa240\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx0\hyphpar0\faauto\ls19\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {Under section 6 Social Security (Incapacity for Work) Act 1994 the statutory instrument by which the Secretary of State exercises the power to make regulations \'93
shall not be made unless a draft of the instrument has been laid before Parliament and approved by a resolution of each House\'94; in other words the making of the regulations is subject to the affirmative resolution procedure.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.\tab}Sections 170 \endash  174 Social Security Administration Act 1992 (\'93the 1992 Act\'94
) contained further provisions governing the procedure for making and amending regulations. By section 9 Social Security Act 1980 the Social Security Advisory Committee (\'93the Committee\'94
) was constituted. This is an independent advisory committee, described by the Commissioner (in paragraph 13 of his decision) as \'93a body of people of great distinction and experience in public life generally, and in particular on social issues\'94.

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 8.\tab}Section 170(1) of the 1992 Act provided for the continuation in being of the Committee:
\par }\pard\plain \s24\qj \li720\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\'93(a)  to give (whether in pursuance of a reference under this Act or otherw
ise) advice and assistance to the Secretary of State in connection with the discharge of his functions under the relevant enactments ... \'94
\par }\pard\plain \s25\qj \li0\ri0\sb240\sa240\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {
The relevant enactments include the Social Security Contributions and Benefits Act 1992 and the 1992 Act. By section 170 (4):
